properties.adr_address: St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.formatted_address: St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.name: Riverfront Trail

reviews.text: Off the beaten trail, adjacent to the river, some of Bob Cassidy's (City Museum founder) fascinating work. If you're visiting St Louis for the first time, I'd recommend City Museum over this. If you've been to the City Museum and would like to experience some of Bob's work in a less finished form in an industrial section of the city, this is worth consideration.
We drive 90 miles away to ride the Riverfront Trail in St. Louis.
Lots of abandoned factories and a busy train yard. We must have missed the nice/interesting parts…
Love what they have done

Just did the Bridge Crossing on a beautiful fall evening. The bridge itself is a work of art and absolutely stunning a great compliment to an already fantastic Skyline in St Louis. would love to have had little bit more time to do more exploring it will have to go on the list of things for next time

properties.adr_address: 998 S Leonor K Sullivan Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.formatted_address: 998 S Leonor K Sullivan Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.name: Mississippi Greenway

reviews.text:
Love this bike trail. I’m a lil bummed out they had to close off and reroute the trailhead but I can get over that. All kinds of wildlife! Prairie dogs, deer, bald eagles nest there, and I’ve seen some beautiful striped garden snakes. No need to worry if you don’t like snakes because they’re off in the wooded areas not the trail.

Avoid at night. I got seriously spooked by a pack of coyotes! The trail is not lit and is basically in the middle of nowhere. Even with a lamp I don’t go there at night.

Police bike along the trail in the day and there’s a manned building for bike repairs and relax on the weekends. Only bathroom is there, a bush, or a port-a-potty at the Chain of Rocks bridge. A rest stop is near the end but currently being renovated. Two water fountains along the way so please stay safe in the summer and bring a large water bottle in the summer. The entire stretch is in full sun. Plenty of riders through the entire day so I feel very safe.

So many great opportunities for pictures!
A place where you can see not only graffiti but murals by many talented artists
As a biking trailhead it is was a good spot to get on the trail. But the parking lot was only mud....
Good hike if you enjoy views of the river.
Nice view around the river will go back

properties.vicinity: 998 South Leonor K Sullivan Boulevard, St. Louis

properties.adr_address: 6500 Government Dr, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.formatted_address: 6500 Government Dr, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.name: John F. Kennedy Memorial Forest

reviews.text:
About as close to a forest oasis you are going to get within city limits. We were here in the winter so the pictures are not doing it justice. Some parts are deep enough in the woods where you don't see cars or building anymore.

Combination of concrete, gravel, and dirt paths throughout. Trails are kind of a cluster that go off in crazy directions without a real loop. If you do the actual quasi loop I thinks it's barely a mile.
Great place to hike and meditate. Tranquility and Peace are abundant in this hidden gem in the heart of our urban forest.
Great birding and lots of wildlife.

This is one of the most relaxing places to get away and it's hidden right in the middle of the city. When you're deep inside the densely packed forest, you can hardly hear the nearby highway or any city noises, just birds and the wind. There's multiple walking trails and bike trails, bridges and streams. I visit the forest multiple times a week to recharge and center myself. Especially beautiful and lush in the Spring.

Hidden gem in Forest Park. Trails are rarely crowded, and the ecological restoration has produced wonderful results. The wooded areas are full of native wildflowers in spring, and the savanna areas are full of native flowers in summer. Urban oasis of wildlife.

properties.adr_address: 4379 Hoffmeister Ave, St. Louis, MO 63125, USA
properties.formatted_address: 4379 Hoffmeister Ave, St. Louis, MO 63125, USA
properties.name: Gravois Greenway: Mysun Charitable Foundation Trailhead

reviews.text: Nice and quiet section of the trail.  Especially walking towards Reavis Barracks.  Scenic and peaceful.
Nice smooth and flat trail, very clean restroom as well. Its worth the drive for a good uninterrupted cycle.

This entry point for Grant’s Trail is a great place to get started with your day of cycling or walking. The trailhead was easy to find and parking was readily available. There are always some other people using the trail around, so it doesn’t feel particularly sketchy or unsafe to leave my car/belongings here. I’d recommend this trailhead for people who want to visit Grant’s Trail!

Love this trail! The new trail head at exit 200 is beautiful. It's a super fun trail that's has gentle inclines and declines with some pretty sights. Goes right by Grant's farm so you can usually see the horses. Crosses a few major roads, but is otherwise away from traffic. Smoothness/newness of the pavement varies by section, but even the oldest parts aren't too bumpy.

BEWARE OF CYCLISTS! This trail attracts the less leisurely cyclists, who tend to barrel through at double the trail's speed limit without announcing themselves. Be on constant lookout or you will get run over.

Great paved trail if you like flat with no real hills. Fair amount of intersections, so you have to stop and wait for the light, which can be annoying. Nice-weather weekends are almost always crowded too. If you want distance with running/biking and not a lot of challenge, this is your place!

properties.adr_address: 4257 Northeast Dr, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA

editorial_summary.overview: 1868 park that shows its history with carriage rides, grass tennis courts, a wading pool & a gazebo.

properties.formatted_address: 4257 Northeast Dr, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.name: Tower Grove Park

reviews.text: Mid winter,  spring is beautiful.  Pavilion's can be reserved and wedding's take place by the fountain at the Piper Palm House.  Great place to have wedding, and family photos.  2 separate playgrounds a small one near Grand Blvd. Larger playgrounds by the tennis courts in the center of the park.  The larger playground has a shallow (like a foot or 2 deep) water pond for the kids in the summer. Friday's are food truck days, and sometimes a farmer's market.  Plenty of trails for biking or walking.

Just such a fantastic park! I am lucky enough to live right across the street and do morning walks where are you encounter lots of friendly joggers on the weekends they have the farmers market which is absolutely amazing. Live music WONDERFUL playgrounds that are well maintained AND a splash pad for summer!

Hands down the place to be on Saturday mornings...where what has be the regions largest Farmer's Markets held just about every week of the year!  It's THE place to get best local products made by artisan and vendors and The finest produce gown and sold by real family farms!  Not to mention how awesome the park itself is!  With so many historically significant pavilions and buildings, and being right next to the botanical garden (originally part of Henry Shaw's property) there are a wide diversity of ornamental and native trees/shrubs, as well as wide open spaces to enjoy a little bit of nature near the heart of St. Louis.

It has a lot of nature in the spring and beautiful structures with beautiful birds and a clean and safe environment. When I go there, I really feel a sense of comfort and different nationalities are seen.

Tower Grove Park is a wonderful place to go for a walk, toss or kick a ball around, hear some music, visit the popup farmers market, food trucks are there periodically and when they're not, there are eateries in walking distance on Grand Boulevard.

properties.adr_address: St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.formatted_address: St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.name: Prairie Boardwalk

reviews.text: Best boardwalk this side of the Mississippi.

properties.adr_address: 13th St & Sidney Street, St. Louis, MO 63118, USA
properties.formatted_address: 13th St & Sidney Street, St. Louis, MO 63118, USA
properties.name: Aboussie Park

reviews.text: Just a small community park in Soulard, overlooking the highway. Nice for a stroll or a quick geocache adventure!

Nice spot. Highway noise is present, but not overbearing. Green grass, some benches, and a sweet gazebo that was recently remodeled. It also happens to be the smallest city park in St. Louis. Must see!

It's private and somehow it seems very secluded, honestly feels tucked away but yet viewing all the hustle and bustle :-)
Being truthful  there's not anyone is on that street unless they live their or they're cutting through
IT'S NICE. THERE ARE BIRDS. THERE IS A POKESTOP AND A GAZEBO. WHAT MORE COULD YOU WANT?
Great experience.  Great site.  Always so pleasant of an experience.

properties.adr_address: 3900 Holly Hills Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63116, USA

editorial_summary.overview: City green space with 2 small stocked fishing ponds, one with pergolas shading the docks.

properties.formatted_address: 3900 Holly Hills Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63116, USA
properties.name: Carondelet Park

reviews.text: Great park in the middle of South City.  Wonderful loop paved walking/running trail around the perimeter of the park.  Picturesque lake and pavillion in the center.  Lots of parking.  Great option to get some some time with nature without leaving the city.  Also have pickelball courts, a playground, horseshoe pits, and fishing in the lake.
I love it. Great place to get some fresh air and for taking picture. There's some trash here and there (not a big deal) should be easy to clean. Great for fishing too!

I grew up near this park and have many good memories in relation to it. I joined my first t-ball team as a young child and played my first game in this park. I was so young that when I ran to 1st base I passed it by and instead ran to my parents on the sidelines. Other memories I have include feeding the ducks after church with my father and as I got older taking my siblings to play frisbee on the weekends. The reality is nowadays in the evening after dark I wish it was patrolled better by police because there seems to be a lot of shenanigans going on.  I would hate for anything to happen to this park. I also greatly appreciate the good neighborhoods that surround it... It is without question my favorite park for walking my dogs.

really pretty park :) a lot of fun walking around and going around on bikes >:) a little rough where there a huge trees and places where you can fall down a hill but just stay careful and you'll be ok :) tenis court and the ymca is right next by !! :)

Its absolutely beatful!! My boyfriend and I decided to check this place out its a little curvy trying to find once your in Crondelet Park but its there. We went to fish and it was huge area all we caught were little carp but it was the experience of it. I'll send a video of it. Enjou

properties.adr_address: 345 North Rd W, St. Louis, MO 63125, USA

editorial_summary.overview: 19th-century army outpost still in use, with numerous outbuildings set aside as historical exhibits.

properties.formatted_address: 345 North Rd W, St. Louis, MO 63125, USA
properties.name: Jefferson Barracks Park

reviews.text: My family and I absolutely love JB! I grew up a block away from there and now I have the privilege of taking my son there as well and I truly hope that it continues for the generations to come. We come here all year round. There are several different activities you can choose from. However summertime is our favorite because we love swimming at the pool. It's cheap and it's got multiple areas to play in. There's a rock climbing wall, lazy river, splash pad, 12' high dive, a regular diving bored, a pool that's 5ft deep, and a water slide. I definitely recommend taking the family.

Lots of trails, and plenty of nature. So many neat things to do. Hiking trails, archery, disc golf, seasonal events, etc. A great place to bring the family and enjoy the outdoors. If you're looking for something to do, don't forget about visiting local parks. It was a great day, and had a blast hanging out here.

The WWII reenactment was well worth the visit. There was SO much to see. The time and care these people take to collect, restore and educate you on this incredibly important memorabilia and teach you about the history of our military is truly inspirational.

A beautiful park in south Saint Louis County. History abounds from the Civil War through World War II.  Informative museums and the expanded Greenway Trail makes for a lovely afternoon!  Highly recommended!

Disc golf course(s)
Some of the best disc golf courses in the area.
A nice mix between the two that are located right next to one another.
The classic course is much more open than the Bunker course.
The Bunker is definitely for more "seasoned" players and I would recommend beginners to stick to the classic course until they develop more control of their discs and a better understanding of disc selection as well as situation awareness.
Both courses can easily be played back to back as long as you arrive early because this is most certainly one of the busiest parks in the area.
Go early
Stay late
Practice
Practice
Practice

properties.adr_address: 5595 Grand Dr, St. Louis, MO 63112, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Opened in 1876, this 1,300-acre park includes 3 museums, a zoo, athletic fields & golf courses.

properties.formatted_address: 5595 Grand Dr, St. Louis, MO 63112, USA
properties.name: Forest Park

reviews.text: This park is amazing. The only parks I've been to that compare are Central Park and Golden Gate. It absolutely massive and beautifully designed and laid out. You can spend a few days exploring all there is to see. The art museum and the zoo are both free and world class. I had a great time exploring and taking pictures.

This is a fantastic park.  It is larger than Central Park.  The St Louis Zoo is located here.  The naturescape area is really unique.    I haven't seen that before.  My daughter loved it.  I didn't get to see the boatyard, but I did drive by.  It would be a great area for walking, running, biking, etc.

The park is located just off the highway and only a few minutes from downtown.  Also, the zoo is FREE (unless you consider parking).  I truly wish there was a park like this where I live.

Love this place!! It has great walking trails,  gardens, wooded areas and streams through out the park. Great things for the family;  from a great park, a zoo and discovery animals to play and ride on, and picnic areas.  Every part of the park has something to offer! A planetarium,  boat house, jewelbox, zoo, history and art museum all free to the public. Also a golf course for the adults.

Passing through and made a quick stop here. Dog friendly park. Beautiful area to walk around and see the grounds. Zoo is also in this area. I didn't go there but saw the entrance as I was exiting the park. It was beautiful with metal sculptures.

This is a gorgeous park situated in a perfect part of town. Plenty of trails to walk with benches scattered throughout to rest and enjoy nature. Tennis courts, kayaking, canoeing, golf, trails, benches and plenty of open spaces for kites and picnicking make this entire park a picture-perfect spot to relax and explore.

properties.adr_address: 6154 Etzel Ave, St. Louis, MO 63133, USA
properties.formatted_address: 6154 Etzel Ave, St. Louis, MO 63133, USA
properties.name: St. Vincent Greenway Trailhead: Trojan Park

reviews.text: I love what they have done to this park!! Major overhaul and it's very clean and safe. It is great for the children of the community!!!!

I've driven past MANY times never payed attention. After attending my lil cousins b day I saw that there's EXERCISE EQUIPMENT THAT'S FUNCTIONAL & CLEAN. GONNA BE RIDING MY BIKE UP THERE B4 WINTER HITS😎
We attended Trojan on its grand opening this park is amazing and is functional as when it was developed ,its been an field day out for our daycare ,clean and location is centralized!
Just had my daughter's 4th birthday party at this park!! Everyone had a nice time. Only complaint is it was a lot of trash we had to pick up from the previous day, and the bathrooms were disgusting!
Small but mighty park. Never knew it was here. Pass by it often. Now I know. Awesome little park. Will definitely visit again.

properties.adr_address: 13002 Bellefontaine Rd, St. Louis, MO 63138-1606, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Site of a former military installation on 300+ riverfront acres with trails, wetlands & wildlife.

properties.formatted_address: 13002 Bellefontaine Rd, St. Louis, MO 63138, USA
properties.name: Fort Belle Fontaine

reviews.text:
Hiked the loop trail with a group of 6, plus my pup for an early Saturday afternoon visit in November 2021. It measured 4.34 miles with an elevation gain of 298 feet and completed it in under 2 hours. We took a very leisurely pace to enjoy the fall colors, sit beside the river, and explore the fort itself.

Highly recommend for an easy and decently brief scenic hike close to the city.

It was nice to see a security guard on post keeping an eye on a historical location. The trails are well kept. Deer were abundant! Got within 10ft of a doe while walking the trail. Beautiful views. Grounds are well kept.

Never knew about this place until St. Louis County Parks advertised a hike and eagle watch event on Facebook. 01.21.23 Hike was amazing! Oh, thanks also for the special treat of hot chocolate. 😊 Huge thank you to the volunteers who led an informative walk through the grounds, down to Coldwater Creek, then along the Missouri River. If you are a novice hiker no worries. Walk was mostly flat with exception of getting down to the creek, and even then the decline was gradual. A beautiful place with lots of history. Can't wait to go back during  spring, summer, and fall to explore.

I agree with others, this is a hidden gem! The various ruins, Missouri river and also the beautiful exposed bedrock along Cold Water creek were unexpected!
I wish there was more historical info on the various ruins, but I understand park funding isn’t the best.
My only issue was a LOT of dog poop on the trails (and dog poop bags, empty and full) especially the first 1/4 mile. I am assuming that’s bc there is a police dog training school nearby but noted this is a trail heavily used by dog owners too.

This place was a real surprise the limestone staircase is pretty cool, but what I thought was even cooler was the limestone riverbank where my dog and I found a cavernous stream. All of the stonework was added using onsite limestone in the 30's as a new deal project, interesting 🤔

properties.adr_address: 9601 Duke Dr, St. Louis, MO 63136, USA
properties.formatted_address: 9601 Duke Dr, St. Louis, MO 63136, USA
properties.name: Maline Greenway Trailhead: Bella Fontaine West County Park

reviews.text: Great neighborhood park with a playground, basketball court and picnic pavilion (Major Whistler Shelter).  The trail now connects all the way to City of Bellefontaine Rec Center on Bellefontaine Road (several miles away)!

my own kinda space.... I'm a outside kinda  person people say good things and bad things about this park but depends on the day and what's going on.... If you see something not good and shouldn't be there or immature things going on...there is a number to call to report it park rangers will come trust me.... 👀

Parents from neighborhood allow teens to stroll park and reek havoc. No supervision and profanity is quite frequent. Also ran across a used condom a few times here. My son has football practice here three times per week. Or else I would never come here

This is a nice park. Michelle DeShay, the Mayor of Moline Acres hosted a community event. The event included free food, give a ways, and a nice parade. They also had nice vendors and radio station 104.1 was there to hype the crowd. Thanks Mayor DeShay for trying to create a positive environment. See ya next year!
That park is a JOKE IT was nothing like that when I moved out here & I hadn't been to that park in a long long while so so so sad 😞😞

properties.adr_address: 5595 Grand Dr, St. Louis, MO 63112, USA
properties.formatted_address: 5595 Grand Dr, St. Louis, MO 63112, USA
properties.name: Forest Park Forever

reviews.text: Alwaya BEAUTIFUL !!! 6 MILES ... SOCIAL DISTANCE IS HARD WHILE YOU WORK OUT I can't breathe with the mask so the shield it is... #staysafe
Selectively enforces Park department rules.  Never updates FAQ. Fails to follow up and even co-signs )in approval) on post showing they broke the rules.
Absolutely love this organization and the work they do for and in Forest Park. A great local nonprofit to get involved with!
Bery friendly staff
Have worked here for 15years

properties.adr_address: 806 Cliff Cave Rd, St. Louis, MO 63129, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Long limestone formation gated to protect bats, with natural grounds & river for picnics & hiking.

properties.formatted_address: 806 Cliff Cave Rd, St. Louis, MO 63129, USA
properties.name: Cliff Cave County Park

reviews.text: Such a beautiful park along the Mississippi! Full of off beaten trails with obstacles to hike that lead to streams, bluffs, the infamous cave, and so much more. Great for exploring or going on a leisurely stroll with friends and family.

This is a beautiful place to go hiking with well maintained concrete and dirt trails with amazing bike trails too! This park has a cave on the lower part of the hill across from the bridge. I'd recommend going down to see it if you can
Peaceful and Beautiful! A lovely place to walk and see Nature's Beauty! Many different birds singing, Deer throughout the trail. Wild Flowers and wonderful scenery!

(Febuary 26, 2022) I went on the day after my birthday to celebrate with a friend. Had such an amazing time, so beautiful and great memories were made. Fun time for a walk and seeing some beautiful scenery.
What a beautiful place to go. The paved trail makes it easy for all ages. I'll have to bring my puppy back here.

properties.adr_address: 4800 Meramec Bottom Rd, St. Louis, MO 63128, USA
properties.formatted_address: 4800 Meramec Bottom Rd, St. Louis, MO 63128, USA
properties.name: Lower Meramec Park,Trails, & Lake

reviews.text: Love this trail, it's a great trail just 1.5 miles each way.  Not to crazy with hills, full of nature & shade.  Returned for the 1st time in over 160 days because of flooding and only the 1st Mile was open but they were working hard at getting it completely open.
Quiet an serene...well except for the highway rumble, but further on the trail it is quiet and beautiful walk by the river.

My family loves his trail. It's just the right distance for our 4 kids to make the 1 mile point where hey have a view of the river a d then make the 1 mile walk back. Mostly flat and smooth asphalt.  Usually some people along the trial, yet still remains private with all the winding trails through the trees. It is so peaceful. We all feel safe and the place is always clean!

I love this place! I bike here almost every day. It is a great, wide, and well paved trail for walking, jogging, skating, biking, or playing with your dog. There are multiple access points down to the river for fishing or canoeing. There are two parking lots. The one closest to the highway is much smaller but easy to access. Down the road a ways it's a much larger parking lot that also has a double outhouse style restroom. This place is very clean. You don't see litter UNLESS it was washed up by a flood. Thank you park ranger and fellow citizens for keeping this place safe and clean! Two trash cans, one at each each end of the trail. There is a bench if you access the trail from the farthest parking lot. But only the one 😕 The paved trail is a little over 2 miles long so it's a 4 mile trip to the car and back though the ride is easy and you can make 2 or three laps without realizing just how far you've gone. There are also many trails off the pavement if you prefer walking on gravel or dirt. 3/4 of the trail provides shade under a canopy of trees. Likewise about 3/4 of the trail provides a view of the river. In my personal experience everyone there is very pleasant. No obnoxious riders or egotistical joggers that feel they own the trail. Everyone observes manners. Bikers don't crowd the walkers and likewise a group of joggers will move over for bikers. Pet owners keep the grounds clean. I've seen a mess on the trail only once and it was gone by my second lap. Grass near the pavement is well maintained and trails through the woods are also maintained. No motorized vehicles allowed for which I'm thankful in this case. No park ranger on site that I've ever seen. Not until it's time to close at dusk. This place is great! Easy to find, it's right off the exit.

This trail is great for walking or biking. The main trail is paved and takes you along with Meramec River. There are two entry points with parking and you can begin your walk either way. The parking lot on the entry that is farther west is a larger lot. There is a combination of shade and open spaces and the trail is mostly flat. The scenery is nice and the only downfall is that when you get closer to the highway, there is more traffic noise. It is a great trail that has easy access.

properties.adr_address: 12450 W Watson Rd, St. Louis, MO 63127, USA
properties.formatted_address: 12450 W Watson Rd, St. Louis, MO 63127, USA
properties.name: Watson Trail Park

reviews.text: Across the street from the park next to the driving range is a converted 18 hole course, to disc golf.  Fantastic course, well maintained, signs are sparse but use the map I added to photos or should one by the small parking lot next to the range.  A great course with many challenges, long over 10,000 .  It will challenge you!! Great fun, nicely maintained so you can find the next tee.  Lots of water and Fescue(long high grass) bright disc and careful shots.  This course will bring you to the next level.  Enjoy!

I love this park because it has a lot of interactive features. There are plenty of ducks and feeders throughout the trail around the lake. It stops people from feeding them bread! Lots of critters living happily here and cool playgrounds for kids.
Beautiful, well cared for park. Great playground areas with nicely paved trails. The lake and surrounding area is beautiful. Fishing is available for $2.00 adults and $1.00 children. Feed the ducks.

This is my favorite Park! Brought my kids here when they were children and they attended summer camp for years..I would go alone sometimes and sit by the lake and reflect on my life or jus recharge..walked the trails, fed the ducks, picniked at the pavillion ,ran from the geese and swam in the pool. Now I bring my grandkids! So much fun and making more memories!

We visited this park on Sunday and had a great time. My grandson enjoyed the different types of climbing structures. The park has a little bit of everything.

Why do the engineers/planners have to plant trees so close to the playground area? The park personnel are not going to clean up the play area.

properties.adr_address: St. Louis, MO 63127, USA
properties.formatted_address: St. Louis, MO 63127, USA
properties.name: Laumeier Sculpture Park Trail Head

reviews.text: Nice about 1.5 mile paved stroller-friendly trail with lots of beautiful sculptures. It's one of its kind trail in south st louis, surrounded by lush green well-maintained gardens & variety of trees. Overall, it's a Day-well-spent kind of place for all age groups. Must visit for nature-lovers as well as art-lovers.

As an artist that makes ceramics, paintings, and various other forms of art I sometimes find it hard to appreciate some sculptures. park itself is ok, however you may see owls in the woods along the trails just left of the entrance which is pretty cool. The park offers a lot of space for picnics and also have some tables to sit at.
Wish we had more time there is a lot to explore. Dog-friendly lots of open space and interesting art.

My favorite park since I was a small child. I used to go here for art camp and gives me great memories still to this day  Taken my dogs there gives me so much joy and I feel more relaxed. I highly recommend it to anyone that needs to escape for just a couple hours or ev n the whole day.

An awesome park with giant post modern and abstract sculptures. The scale of the artwork is hard to understand until you experience it. This unique park is one of St Louis’s most unforgettable treasures. Children and adults love it. The huge open spaces are broken with larger than life sculptures. The whole park is surrounded by beautiful woods. It takes about 45 -120 minutes to wander through the whole park. There are also trails in the woods.

properties.adr_address: 11991 Stoneywood Dr, St. Louis, MO 63122, USA

editorial_summary.overview: A river meanders through woodlands on this placid, 93-acre retreat featuring hiking & picnicking.

properties.formatted_address: 11991 Stoneywood Dr, St. Louis, MO 63122, USA
properties.name: Emmenegger Nature Park

reviews.text:
By far my favorite park to hike in Saint Louis metropolitan area. Located right along the Missouri River. Beautiful views galore for those who enjoy photography. Tons of trails to explore, both paved and off-beaten paths. Dried up riverbeds littered with fossils. Bluffs that cut-through and overlook the entire area.  'Challenging' obstacles such as having to walk across logs to get from one point to another. Lots of wildlife (I've come across many deer and even wild turkey).

Decent size, but still small enough to where you can bring your family, friends, and pets without having to worry about anyone getting lost. Cell phones still have service. The perfect combination of nature and civilization!! Can't wait to go back this year. 😎

Great park for walking or hiking right next to the Meramac River and 44. Plenty of trails, some paved and unpaved. When doing the bluff trail start counterclockwise to save the best views for closer to the end. Nothing seems to be marked very well so I would suggest the All Trails App or some other trail app unless you have a decent sense of direction. Fun park that you could explore for a couple hours easily.
This is a great park to get in some much needed steps. There are different trails to take for the level of hiking you are looking for. And it great if you want to go off trail as well.

Pretty cool place to hike! Sweet views with a couple different trails. We went up the hill to the top where it ends at a field with some apricot trees. Picked some and took them home. Saw a ton of deer. But on the way back we saw a lady talking to the cops after she caught someone breaking into her car. So keep it empty if you plan to park here

A hidden gem for all abilities to explore. A well cleaned and paved trail and tons of offshoots to go wonder in. Never had the same adventure there twice. People are friendly and even when packed they are never too busy

properties.adr_address: 137 E Waymire Ave, Webster Groves, MO 63119-1744, USA
properties.formatted_address: 137 E Waymire Ave, Webster Groves, MO 63119, USA
properties.name: Lorraine Davis Park

reviews.text: Nice basic area with a clean and balanced walking path. Lots of nature to observe and a huge pedestrian bridge for the kids to play on.
The creek is toxic. There was a hobo laying down under pavilion. Do not want to walk next to sewage.
Serene location for the most part.  Never seen any problems there.  Great for a small gathering
Very peaceful and beautiful place that my son's and I enjoy as often as possible
Trailhead has small shelter and picnic tables. No restrooms. Along the Deer Creek trail

properties.adr_address: 2701 Finestown Ave, St. Louis, MO 63129, USA
properties.formatted_address: 2701 Finestown Ave, St. Louis, MO 63129, USA
properties.name: Bee Tree County Park

reviews.text: Very beautiful park to walking or taking fall photo. It is clean and super beautiful for picnic. There are place to sit near the lake and playground.  Gku could fish and grill.
We used the overlook for a wedding, The location is amazing! 100% recommend. The rest of the park is nice too.
Such a beautiful park with a great view of the mighty Mississippi river. It was sad to see the water levels so low after having first seen it 3 years ago.

It was a lovely park with a nice fishing lake.  There was a gravel trail around the lake. The kids liked the playground. I would have liked an information board about any trails. I also thought I'd be able to see the Mississippi river. I couldn't find access to the river.
What I enjoy most about Bee Tree Park is the Cedar Trail. I enjoy walking my dog there the most. It's quiet, has great fresh air, and my dog loves it!

properties.adr_address: 1 Lone Elk Park Rd, Valley Park, MO 63088-2032, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Sprawling space with driving routes to see elk, bison & other wildlife, plus morning feedings.

properties.formatted_address: 1 Lone Elk Park Rd, Valley Park, MO 63088, USA
properties.name: Lone Elk Park

reviews.text:
Lone elk is very cool. Our family has been only 3 times now but it's been a few  great experiences. You can walk trails get to see the bison, elk, deer and they even have a bird sanctuary. Although I haven't been to see the birds. There is a pretty cool lookout at the beginning of the drive. We went on a trail our last time there and got to see some bison up close. Not too close... just a great place to go and see nature and have a nice picnic.
Oh we also found a dog statue I believe was a good cache. We wasn't doing the geo caches but we spotted the dog.. apologies for the camera focus.

Lone Elk Park is such a magical place. From the sun beaming down on the lake with the hills surrounding it as you are driving. The grasslands, the wooded areas and the beautiful animals roaming around. The bison, the elk, deer, birds and other local wild life just living their little lives. This is a perfect park to just have your windows down, no music and to just enjoy nature. I often like to sit down and watch what the animals are doing for hours on end watching them graze and live life just as we do. This is a perfect place to take your family and boy do the animals get close so be careful!

Absolutely beautiful place. Hidden gem in the St. Louis, MO trip. We had to kill a whole afternoon and evening before our flight out. This was a stress free ride through, seeing elks, bisons, friendly raccoons acting cute (don't fall for it) as you drive by. We took the loop twice. Nature's beauty at it's best.

We never tire of driving through. Each time, we see something different. And, it always delights my elderly mother. This latest visit, there was a newborn elk along with baby raccoons and a growing bison calf.

Had a great walk at Lone Elk County Park with my wonderful wife! Not only were the fall colors starting to show their brilliance, the temperature was perfectly balanced with a steady breeze that made it extremely enjoyable to hike around. We ate lunch about halfway into our hike on White Boson Trail at a spot overlooking the lake and it was magical to see the sparkling water! What’s more, we were treated to a cornucopia of wildlife during the last 1/4 mile of our hike: majestic elk, wandering deer, moseying raccoons, munching chipmunks, and scampering squirrels!  Then, we saw some bison laying about with an armadillo rooting around as we were driving out! Can’t beat fall hiking! #Fall #missouri #nature #naturelovers #hiking #hikingadventures #naturephotography #outdoors #outdoorphotography

properties.vicinity: 1 Lone Elk Park Road, Valley Park

properties.adr_address: 9801 Green Park Rd, St. Louis, MO 63123, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Green expanse with a playground, sports fields, shaded picnic area & jogging paths.

properties.formatted_address: 9801 Green Park Rd, St. Louis, MO 63123, USA
properties.name: Officer Blake C. Snyder Memorial Park

reviews.text: It's a nice park. We've been a couple times for geocaching and a good walk. There are paved trails but also unpaved paths in the woods. I saw baseball fields but I'm not sure what other amenities there are.

Nice, short paved trail. There looks to be some trails through the woods too. Yet it was too muddy when I went so didn't check those out. I also think it's great they renamed this trail after the fallen Officer.
Great spot for casual walking. Trails are paved and pretty flat. Lots of space, doesn't feel crowded even when it's busy.

A hidden treasure just off St. Louis Downtown! This park has trails, an awesome picnic spot, a large covered area for barbecuing, a lawn and trails, paved and unpaved. It's really easy to get to and located a little off the exit 199 from I-55. The other approach is from S. Lindbergh.

We spent about half a day here and enjoyed our time. We did three trails and used the 'gym' equipment that's located conveniently along the trail. The floor for it is a soft mat that you can be certain to protect you even if you fall while fooling around. I realized our gym at the apartment doesn't have these facilities as an outdoor park!

Pack a picnic basket and go here. You can relax. Run with your pet if that's your thing. Play ball. Throw a frisbee. There's room for everyone and everything. The park is beautiful and well maintained.

The Snyder memorial Park is yet another example of poor marketing by St. Louis. It took us two years to realize that a park like this exists not so far from Costco at Rusty Road!
Great park for a walk, it’s quiet but be prepared for bikes and dogs though as it’s part of grants trail

properties.adr_address: 9245 Whitecliff Pk Ln, St. Louis, MO 63126, USA
properties.formatted_address: 9245 Whitecliff Pk Ln, St. Louis, MO 63126, USA
properties.name: Whitecliff Park

reviews.text: Quite a bit to do here. Pool is very good. Nice playground. Tennis and basketball courts. Decent little series of trails in the woods that take you near Gravois Creek, the quarry (now open for fishing), with several different trailheads. Pretty easy to explore it all in under an hour.
Great suburban greenscape and trail park. An amazing waterway/creek runs though and the quarry is a visual treat.
Beautiful place! Great for a short or long trek.

The main thing that I want to say about Whitecliff Park is please don't go there because I enjoy having it to myself .....it's a small Park and unless it falls on the trail they don't pick it up.... my old dog and I have been enjoying the trails for 16 years but please leash your dog if you're going to come here it's quite scary to run across one that has run from its owner ...
My Kiwanis Club used the gym for a Trivia Night. The facilities and staff were outstanding.

properties.adr_address: 10820 Riverview Dr, St. Louis, MO 63137, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Mile-long 1929 Mississippi River bridge with a trademark 30-degree turn is open to bikers & walkers.

properties.formatted_address: 10820 Riverview Dr, St. Louis, MO 63137, USA
properties.name: Old Chain of Rocks Bridge

reviews.text: Shame the area isn’t more positively developed.  Amazing views, very peaceful and relaxing.  A few signs with some Route 66 information.  Well worth the journey to get there.  Unfortunately, both sides are a bit sketchy.  The only parking is on the Illinois side after a long drive down a road with questionable buildings at its entrance.  The only restroom is on the Missouri side, a port-a-potty.  I hope in the future some positive development can take place to make this a location people will want to visit more frequently.

Amazing bridge. Great walk on a piece of historical Rt. 66. Best time for photo is near sunset. One mile bridge across the Mississippi River. So plan at least one hour for a round trip. Bridge will be cleared by police at around 9:15pm in June.

This bridge is such a great place to walk, rides bikes, road trip and so much more. It has been fun going magnet fishing off the bridge. Also, this is such a great spot for photography! Not only are you 90 feet up in the air, but you can see so much for miles and miles. Makes photography easy (ollland real nice

So cool, what a day to just enjoy the views. Historic a comfortable Mile walk across the bridge, enjoy the birds flying, scan the river banks for people fishing. Excellent opportunity for walkers or bicycling.

We parked on the IL side of the bridge. It was raining off and on, but the walk across the bridge was so fun that the rain didn't matter. There are 2 spotting scopes on the bridge for viewing distant places. One has a wheelchair accessible ramp. The views were great and the bridge is very solid and secure. The only downfall is that the "public restroom" located at the Missouri end of the bridge was a very full, very smelly port-a-potty.

properties.adr_address: Grand Basin, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.formatted_address: Grand Basin, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.name: Grand Basin

reviews.text: So nice a relaxing or you can go for a walk or run.  People even take wedding pictures or have picnics on the grounds.

I usually only go when it's warm outside, but last year I stopped by during after a snowfall and it was so beautiful. This place can get crowded but for the most part it is peaceful. Especially during the winter. It's a great place to park and get some steps in around the basin. You can bird watch here, climb art hill for an added workout, or just sit and take it all in. One of my favorite places to sit at night before the park closes.
We were married here 2/26/23
It was just so refreshing getting out and collaborating with nature today. The Grand Basin was the perfect spot.
#1 favorite place to spend my time in St. Louis. Zoo is walking distance and the art Museum. Best place for a picnic!

properties.adr_address: 3115 Franklin Ave, St. Louis, MO 63106, USA
properties.formatted_address: 3115 Franklin Ave, St. Louis, MO 63106, USA
properties.name: Chambers Park

reviews.text: Some guys were shooting hoops and a few were playing music from their cars, I was just parked to make phone calls but I think they have a free pool during summer if you live in the area

Pool and bathrooms were closed. Kids playground had a lot of trash. We spent a little while picking up, but there was a lot there. Kids liked the play structure. We were the only ones there on a Saturday morning.
Chambers Park is one of the best parks in the city of Saint Louis it has a good diverse mix of people the footing trails in the mix of Wildlife and fauna and Flora is exquisite a must-see
Great place to play baseball or run away with the kids. I wish therr was a gate to all around the park but its not so bad

Its it's a clean Serene type place to take your kids to and sit out get on the swings run around burn some energy just enjoy the aura of the scenery in the nice quiet atmosphere that a lot of parks have and this is one that has nice quietness

properties.adr_address: Pernod Ave & Jamieson Avenue, St. Louis, MO 63139, USA
properties.formatted_address: Pernod Ave & Jamieson Avenue, St. Louis, MO 63139, USA
properties.name: Lindenwood Park

reviews.text: Beautiful park in a nice area! The playground is up to date and very clean. The foam ground cover is much nicer than mulch or pebbles. There are lots of trees and open areas, and  plenty of street parking. The playground has a neat rope climbing structure, a 2-5 playground and a 5-12 playground so lots to do for all ages.
Attended a festival here.  Park was very nice and clean.  The festival was a god time.
Reserved a pavilion for our daughter's birthday.  Great time!

Such a pretty, peaceful, clean and family oriented  park. It had other people there including kids, however it was so nice and quiet that we were all able to enjoy lunch and have conversation. I would definitely go back! The equipment for the children so play on, looks as though it was brand new. There were tennis court and picnic tables that all had a covering, that helped us get away from the 102 degree weather today!
Best Park in the area for family fun. Concerts. Playground. Lots of parking. Food trucks sometimes too.

properties.vicinity: Pernod Ave & Jamieson Avenue, St. Louis

properties.adr_address: Parking lot, 601 S Holmes Ave, Kirkwood, MO 63122, USA
properties.formatted_address: Parking lot, 601 S Holmes Ave, Kirkwood, MO 63122, USA
properties.name: Grant's Trail Mile 10

reviews.text: Great trail to take a walk, ride a bike, or skate. Cyclist have forgotten trail etiquette and sneak up on you without a courtesy "on your left" Lance Armstrong would be upset.... and if you walk your dog and don't have bags, get them into the grass before they drop a deuce.

We did a short walk from the trailhead to the Sappington House. We pushed my 90 year old mom in a transit chair which proved a bit challenging.  Pushing her was not the issue, but there are drainage grooves and seams in the asphalt that required lifting the wheels over and frequently coming to an abrupt stop.
I'm not sure what could be done to smooth out these bits but it mainly occurred between the trailhead and the 9 5 mile marker. After that, down to the cemetery and Sappington House was pretty smooth.
Would love to go back when I have more time or have my bike with me.
One of the best in the state. Thank God it's closer to the city.

Grant's Trail is a great urban paved bike trail.   It is roughly 10 miles from the Kirkwood trailhead to the intersection at Germania for a nice 20 mile out and back all on paved trail.  If you continue north of Germania it eventually meets the Greenway near Carondelet Park.
Great trail to ride on, nice gradual incline but still manageable

properties.vicinity: Parking lot, 601 South Holmes Avenue, Kirkwood

properties.adr_address: 1 Lone Elk Park Rd, Valley Park, MO 63088, USA
properties.formatted_address: 1 Lone Elk Park Rd, Valley Park, MO 63088, USA
properties.name: White Bison Trailhead

reviews.text: First time here today, and I really enjoyed it! It was very Serene. I was the only one on the trail. It is a 3.2 mile Loop, but I must have missed the loop part, so I added on an extra mile to find my car.🥴
Beautiful park and a very nice hike. Saw plenty of elks but unfortunately didn't get to see the bisons. Only watch out for ticks..
The bison have some babies now, time to check them out at Lone Elk Park.
Beautiful hiking trail
Part of Lone Elk State Park and the whole experience there was wonderful

properties.vicinity: 1 Lone Elk Park Road, Valley Park

properties.adr_address: 1401 Kiefer Creek Rd, Ballwin, MO 63021, USA

editorial_summary.overview: A leisure destination for St. Louisans in the early 1900s, now popular for hiking & mountain biking.

properties.formatted_address: 1401 Kiefer Creek Rd, Ballwin, MO 63021, USA
properties.name: Castlewood State Park

reviews.text: I'm not a nature person at all or one to consider hiking as a fun outing. However, I must say that I was beyond impressed with Castlewood State Park! I am not into exercise or fitness, but I am very much in love with the hiking trail here. It's a beautiful leisurely stroll with minimal exertion that you will wish wasn't over just yet as you reach the end. October is my favorite time to visit with all of the gorgeous colors. We hit the 2.7 miles trail around 10:30 a.m. which takes 2.5-3 hours with resting, gazing, playing & pictures. Afterwards, we enjoy a picnic lunch in one of the open meadows or picnic sites. If you're looking for a free or inexpensive date or family outing that's memorable & enjoyable for everyone, Castlewood will definitely impress you & your loved ones! It's just the perfect amount of outdoor adventure without overdoing it or hearing excessive complaints from tired or bored kiddos. Even the biggest of couch potatoes will love it, so drag your lazy family members too. I promise you will love it!
Without a doubt, this is the best place to hike within the St. Louis area. Great trails and beautiful views!! Fall colors are really starting to show but haven't hit their peak yet.

I’ve been coming here since I was a little kid! Great place to bring the family for hiking and easy nature walks. They have paved and unpacked trails. You can hike, walk, bike and bring your dogs. They have a water front for hot summer days too. Parking is limited when the park gets crazy busy in the summer time but over all this place is a great place for summer hiking!

Lone Elk Park is a great free place to drive through. You can walk the trails, stop at any of the picnic sites or just drive thru. Love coming here. It was a good day to see the velk, buffalo and some deer.

Great Park! The trails are excellent and walking with stream with my dog is one of our favorite shared pastimes! It can get pretty busy during the summer and the trails along the river can flood during heavy rains. Otherwise this is a great spot to run, mountain bike or take in the views from the bluffs!

properties.adr_address: 9227 Sappington Rd, St. Louis, MO 63126, USA
properties.formatted_address: 9227 Sappington Rd, St. Louis, MO 63126, USA
properties.name: Claire Gempp Davidson Memorial Conservation Area

reviews.text: Nice little park with several small trails, some benches and plaques to explain what was once there and the wild life, plants, flowers and trees that still exist within the area.  It's a quick little get away within the city.

Great small park to go for a walk to enjoy nature.  Have a seat on one of the few benches located through out the park.  Sit and enjoy the sounds of nature, unfortunately, you will also hear the sounds of traffic.
Visit the sun dial while you’re here and take a stroll over the pond.
There are public restrooms available on site, I just hope they’re open when you need to go!

Enjoy your walk and please like if this review helps you.

Nice place. A lot of trails in a small area (condensed). The fresh mulch trail is like walking on pillows or a shaggy rug (multiple layers, fresh layer)

Pond has long angled wood bridge overlooking about 20 swimming water turtles, couple ducks and a few goldfish etc

Back sign says the fescue was removed for prairie plants
It's like looking in a box of crayons. Chest high yellows and purples all in bloom (Sept)
I love this place. Doesn't look like much from the road, but it's fairly large, educational and beautiful. What a hidden gem!

This was an outstanding summer escape! Great shade, plant life, birds, and turtles!

Awesome place to take the kids, just be sure to watch out for the poison ivy

properties.adr_address: Grand National Dr, Florissant, MO 63034, USA
properties.formatted_address: Grand National Dr, Florissant, MO 63034, USA
properties.name: Champ Trails

reviews.text: Beautiful hike on this fall day.  Not a difficult hike.  Very scenic.  We were thankful  the falling leaves had covered the trail making it walkable.   It had rained a couple days before.

Wilderness park. No bathrooms, no water, no paved trails. Trails are steep in places. Great place to be in the woods without having to leave the city. Rarely see other humans, but lots of birds, squirrel  and deer. You may spot the occasional coyote or raccoon, but tracks for both are common. Beautiful wild meadow trail on one side of the park, best in spring or in fall during the butterfly migration. And the occasional relic of the past from before the land was given to the country (see photo).
Well marked natural trail. Easy to medium difficulty. Approx. 1 mile long. Love this hike when trying to stay close to home
Great little neighborhood walking trail. Not marked so you have to pay attention. Dog loves it. We go almost daily.
Nice trail. I saw a snake, too!

properties.adr_address: St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.formatted_address: St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.name: Forest Park Hatchery

reviews.text: Got to see a Belted Kingfisher feeding at the hatchery area, which was a special treat!

What a beautiful, peaceful area of Forest Park. My grandson Adus'Ray, who is autistic, at first he was scared of all the water. However, after he watched me walk around taking pictures 📷, he left his mom and ran to me to adventurize the area. It was his Birthday week: he turned 4.

Forest Park is always a pleasure to fun around in . Paddle boats , fishing,art museum, jewel box and muny ,tennis courts and walking paths everywhere and not to forget golf and even rent golf carts as well .Great time for the family or just to get out .
So good, I can smell the fish. Best hatchery I've visited in weeks.
The staff did a great job of showing us the pond ecosystems and how they work.

properties.adr_address: Ballwin, MO 63021, USA
properties.formatted_address: Ballwin, MO 63021, USA
properties.name: River Scene Trail

reviews.text:
Medium difficulty trail with solid incline in the beginning and beautiful views of river. We hiked during light rain and trees protected us.
Stay hydrated.
Probably the most popular trail at Castlewood for good reason.  It's short at 3.1 miles, hills are not bad and views of the Mermac are excellent

Our favorite trail in Castlewood park, takes you along the bluffs for amazing views and down to the river valley all on the same trail. There is definitely a climb involved and quite a few stairs as well but it is completely manageable. Have fun!!!
Easy 2 mile loop hike took us 1 hour to finish. The beautiful view at the top of the trail is worth watching.

Very scenic trail, very picturesque.  Mostly canopy so easily shaded. The beginning is a steep hill that goes for a while. Then stairs on the way down. Flat for the remainder. 3.3 miles we did in under 2 hours with plenty of stops. Bring at least a bottle of water per person. Trailhead starts right across from restrooms near playground.

properties.adr_address: 1675 S Mason Rd, St. Louis, MO 63131, USA
properties.formatted_address: 1675 S Mason Rd, St. Louis, MO 63131, USA
properties.name: Queeny Park

reviews.text: The playground here has very little shade although the kids can keep out of it in the tunnels of the "pyramids". There were lots of people walking  or bicycling around the lake and it is very pretty. You can fish here as well.
Nice dog park for my pup! Trail gave me and my MTN. Bike a good 40 minute workout. Nice climbing slopes.

The perfect place for training runs, the trails are well maintained and marked, and you can loop different segments easily to get the distance you need. Just remember which enterance you parked at, don't leave valuables out and be safe (don't get hit by a deer.)
Wonderful place to be surrounded by nature in West County. Very peaceful. Even saw a turkey once!
The complete Eagle route is 5K (3mile..), perfect walking distance.

properties.adr_address: 1703 Marshall Rd, Kirkwood, MO 63122, USA
properties.formatted_address: 1703 Marshall Rd, Kirkwood, MO 63122, USA
properties.name: Dee Koestering Park

reviews.text: Great spot for a quick hike. Not too crowded. Very hilly, with limited rest stops, so I'd rate this as moderately difficult. Limited parking and alot of road noise from interstate 44. Plenty of wildlife to be seen though. No bathroom, but there access to water at the trailhead. The first hill is brutal! And the overlook isn't all too scenic. Get off the paved trail and down into the valley for the best scenery, definitely worth a few hours to look around.

This tucked away walk is nice but not grand. It's a short walk to the lookout which is paved and a footpath which goes into the quarry. The lookout isn't amazing but has some good info about the place and historical accounts. The footpath is better as you get to see how the rock was quarried and there are blocks leftover from when it was active. Overall not really a park with playgrounds and not a long walk. It does have a steep up and down. If you are interested in an old quarry this would be a good spot to visit and it's ok for kids. No bathroom was on site.

Small park with quite a bit of highway noise. It basically sits in some peoples' backyards so you don't really get the "in nature" feels. Surprising amount of wildlife though, and the  little trail is nice and has some opportunities for climbing large rocks left over from the quarry days. Worth going once.

Sad to day but this is one of the worst trails I've ever been on. The trail was completely neglected and overgrown. And the scenic overlook didn't have much of a view. The only redeeming factor to this park was the convenient location.
If the trails were better maintained, this park would get five stars. If you need to climb some rocks and change your elevation, but don't want to leave the city, this is the place.

properties.adr_address: 4420 Ohio Ave, St. Louis, MO 63111, USA
properties.formatted_address: 4420 Ohio Ave, St. Louis, MO 63111, USA
properties.name: Sugarloaf Mound

reviews.text: I didn’t know this was here until I posted a picture of the billboard on Facebook and asked if anyone knew what it meant. Someone works nearby and had heard about it.

It is wonderful that this burial mound has been preserved and that control has been returned to the Osage Tribe! You can benefit from seeing it from outside of the fence. There are no facilities and parking is very limited.  Contemplate the cultural history represented by this  monument.

This mound is of great significance to the history of the area, from the ancient thriving native civilization here from 600-1300AD to the modern locals that lived there for 90 years, preserving the last remaining mound in "Mound City". Now returned to the Osage Nation, this will be a great place to visit and learn the origins of the area. The interpretive center has not been built yet (as of 2022). There is no parking or admission to the mound for now, so admire and reflect from afar and look for the upcoming venue, but please be patient and do not trespass.
The house is now gone and it's just fenced off. I wish there was signage stating the significance of the mound to St Louis.
The fact that has not been bulldozed is amazing.

properties.adr_address: 1704 S River Rd, St Charles, MO 63303, USA
properties.formatted_address: 1704 S River Rd, St Charles, MO 63303, USA
properties.name: Bangert Island

reviews.text: I love this little spot for hiking with the doggos. It does get very muddy after snow melt/rain so i would recommend giving it a few days to dry up if the weather has been wet.
We bring our kiddos here to hike and we all love it! It's so beautiful, lot's of tree coverage from the sun..so much beautiful nature to explore! Also comes with a beautiful view of the river!

I really like the trails because you can circle around and don't have to repeat a lot of the walk.
You'll see scenic views of the Missouri River, Hollywood Casino, Blanchett Memorial Bridge and more.
Recently the park management of the park changed to City of St. Charles. The signs, and benches have been removed along with a lot of trees.
They have put in a new bridge with hand rails across the creek. I guess they will be putting a lake in where they removed trees in February 2022. Right now the trees look like a big mess, but St. Charles has a path that you can still get to the island to walk or ride bikes.
I haven't ridden bikes on the trails but a lot of people do. I see people walking their dogs and kids too.
Some times there is sand you can climb down to, depending on how high the Missouri River is. There are some drop offs near the trail along the river so watch kids closely if you think they will not pay enough attention to this.
I enjoy walking through the trees in the woods. It's a pretty place. Much more city noise now that they have taken so many trees, but still enjoyable. I'm glad it exists.
Fun trail. Mostly shaded and loops around to see the river.

A little muddy on a January morning.
I liked there was no one around (note, January morning)
Trails are a little
Confusing? We just wandered from trail to trail to trail till we got back to the trail head. Some nice views of the river and even a park bench at one spot.

Minimal parking

properties.adr_address: Manchester, MO 63011, USA
properties.formatted_address: Manchester, MO 63011, USA
properties.name: Hawk Ridge Trail

reviews.text:
Hawk Ridge is a stunning and relaxing trail! There’s a handful of different routes to take. The main trail is about 4 mi with a mix of concrete and gravel walkways. The scenery is beautiful with a few areas to sit and read a book along the way.

It can get a little busy, but it’s not too crowded by any means. You might encounter horses on part of the trail which can be a pleasant surprise.

It’s the perfect way to start the day!

At 4.4 miles, this is the longest of the Queeny Park trails.  It runs basically around the perimeter of the park, including right along Mason Road on the east side.  It is primarily paved but has some rocky sections as well.  A very popular trail!
Quiet scenic trail in West county.  Trail does have several hills.
Nice trails with a few hills to enhance the workout

properties.adr_address: 13998 St Charles Rock Rd, Bridgeton, MO 63044, USA
properties.formatted_address: 13998 St Charles Rock Rd, Bridgeton, MO 63044, USA
properties.name: Riverwoods Park & Trail

reviews.text: Just walked this trail for the first time and it was awesome. Not completely flat but very small hills. Also part of the trail is in the shade which is a huge plus for me. 4 stars because the bridge is out. So u can’t walk the hole trail.

Surprisingly, the beautiful bridge was washed away when we got to it. You can no longer go around the loop. You can do the trail as 2 segments.

We enjoyed the view of the Missouri River, of historic St. Charles on the other side, and of the historic St.Charles Rock Road that no longer crosses the river here.

When I visited there were people painting on canvas under one of the small pavilions that are often used to picnic. There were also people who were dog walking and fishing.

The men's and women's restrooms are clean when I have visited.  The parking area has landscape plants. There is a kiosk for signage when they create some.

The loop is incomplete due to the broken bridge. That makes you travel along the Earth City Business Park which does not smell very nice. The trail is otherwise nice, you can ride your bikes or stroller on the paved surface.
Nice trailhead with bathroom facilities.  Only negative,  the bridge on the loop trail around the river was out, so it was a really short walk
Nice place to walk. Sad that part of the trail is closed. But the views are pretty.

properties.adr_address: 1675 S Mason Rd, St. Louis, MO 63131-1216, USA
properties.formatted_address: 1675 S Mason Rd, St. Louis, MO 63131, USA
properties.name: Tails & Trails Dog Park at Queeny Park(membership)

reviews.text: We absolutely love Queeny Park's Dog Park!  This is a large dog park with sides for both small and large dogs. The large dog side is quite large, I'd say maybe 2 or 3 acres in size, so there's plenty of room to run.  This dog park does require annual memberships, but they also offer Day passes (the day passes can only be obtained at the Greensfelder Complex, which is only open normal weekday hours, FYI!!  You can't get a day pass on the weekend).  Vaccinations documentation for your dog is required for either a day pass or a membership, and the park is maintained and very clean.  Dog parents have always been extremely fast to break up any dust-ups between dogs, although every once in awhile you come across an oblivious owner who knows nothing.   We've been coming to this dog park about 2 years now and we'll continue to go back!  Hot tip:  there are beautiful trails to walk before or after playtime also.

When it’s open, it’s a great dog park. The problem is it’s never open. The number of times I go there on a sunny, warm day to find it padlocked shut is too many to count.

Also vehemently opposed to the idea of requiring a membership to go in. Dog parks should be open and available, especially if it’s in a public park.
Membership only it is not public gotta love our tax dollars being put to waste

As a travel from another state was disappointed not to gain access to this facility.  Fine to wrap it in bureaucrat  rules but your website should so advise so that travelers do not waste time(not totally as my well behaved lab walked off leash on the outside perimeter of the obviously fine dog park!)
Very big,  agility course, and an area that looks like it may have a water mister for summer (with pebbles on the ground)

reviews.text: We always enter from Mason Road, right where the horses are usually unloaded, etc. and have. It had any issues with parking. Queeny is always a beautiful park for long or short hikes, depending on your mood. There are a couple of water features like ponds that are very nice and some steep hills depending on your trail. The loop that goes around the equestrian area has a field of wild flowers and grass and it’s really scenic. Tons of animals, especially deer, and I missed a picture of a falcon on this day! Definitely recommended!

I walk this park all time. It has many great trails that make you feel like you are in the forest and far away from the city. I usually do the Hawk Ridge trail which is around 7mi. It’s pretty much guaranteed you will see deer and other wild life every time. I’ve even seen a white squirrel, which was bizarre. Today I saw this Eastern Box turtle. He was pretty big and probably several years old. Who knows what I’ll find next?
This place is big and beautiful! So much to do. There are multiple trails, playgrounds, and the recreation center. I have found something new every time I've been here!

This place always has the greatest people, and love the equipment. We started playing Mario Bros and I was singing the songs as we ran around playing everyone pretty much had a similar experience, and it was enhanced as I played the music.

We loovvveee Tails & Trails dog park!  Excellent size for our large dogs, and any time there are scuffles between dogs the parents are always quick to resolve the situation.  Great location and kept very clean, with dog water stations during the summer as well (they are turned off during the winter season, bring your own water and bowls).  There is also a shady area with picnic tables for the humans on a hot day.

properties.adr_address: 8 Meramec Station Rd, Valley Park, MO 63088, USA
properties.formatted_address: 8 Meramec Station Rd, Valley Park, MO 63088, USA
properties.name: Meramec Greenway Trailhead: Arnold's Grove

reviews.text:
What a gorgeous, well maintained trail! Stopped by for a little suburban trekking on our way home from Chicago. Planned on trekking 2 miles but enjoyed it so much we ended up doing six! Dogs on leashes are welcome. Moderately high traffic but everyone was courteous so it never felt too crowded.

If you're looking for someplace to stretch your legs, this'll be perfect.

PS - the toilets looked a little sketchy so we just ran up the road, bought a bottle of water, & used the one at the BP station!

At Valley Park's Arnold's Grove Trailhead Park, we enjoyed the views of: the Meramec River, the rapids, the 1923 BNSF 3-span through truss bridge over the Meramec River downstream, the 1929 Union Pacific closed-spandrel arch bridge over Fishpot Creek, and the mouth of Fishpot Creek.

Besides the Meramec Greenway Trailhead, there are benches, a pavilion, and 3 flagpoles. Some fish from the bank of the Meramec River.

There are no restroom facilities nor playground equipment.

Beautiful paved pathway alongside the Meramec River. The color palette is green - trees, grass, maples. Saw 3 deer that were apparently so accustomed to human contact that my friend and I were able to carry on a convo while the deer ambled about for 3 minutes less than 10 feet from us. We took the trail to Simpson Lake, a beautiful lake ringed by trees. There were 4-5 kayaks out there at the time. A couple picnic benches were nearby, too. ~2.5 miles from trailhead to the lake. Scenic walk. Not challenging at all. Saw 4-5 cyclists and an equal number of runners.
Nice little 7 mile-round trip bike ride down and back to the parking.  Scenic along the Meramec River; lots of wooded areas along the path.
Nice trail with lots of wildlife and great views of the river.

reviews.text: At the front of the park is the art gallery where very exquisite art was on display! There were a lot of beautiful art filled with knowledgeable books that were sold at a cost of $5 which are fun table pieces to have for friends! The party leads down into fun filled trails, beautiful art throughout the park, and knowledgeable plaques posted to learn more about the artist and the reason behind the style of art displayed! Beautiful scenery mixed with incredibly large sized art all throughout the park makes for an otter world experience filled with the collision of raw nature and intellectual art! Have fun and soak up the beautiful weather right now!

What a lovely park!   Such a nice area to spend time outdoors and walk -  and the sculptures make it so much more interesting.   Great place for a picnic too.  Some of the sculptures are pretty neat.  And free admission.  We only stayed an hour but you could easily stay for several hours if you want to get your steps in.

Pretty neat little place and it's free. Came here for a quick walk because I was in the area and was able to check out some of the interesting structures that they had on display. Quite family friendly and ample parking. The trails mostly don't have shade so don't come on a hot day.

What a beautiful park!  Huge sculptures everywhere that you look.  It is really a sight to see.  The grounds are trimmed and visitors center is helpful.  Make sure to grab a map while in the center. Truly a neat place.
A Route 66 stop on my journey.  It's free to walk around the grounds and dog friendly. There are many large sculptures to see and appreciate. Many photo ops. Definitely worth a stop.
